Exercise 2: : Factor management

Requirements: Choose one dataset and a variable which is a factor to explore. - Drop factor / levels; - Reorder levels based on knowledge from data.

Drop Oceania

We are going to explore the continent variable in the gapminder dataset. First we need to confirm that it is a factor.

gapminder$continent %>% 
  class()
## [1] "factor"

With the above validation, now lets take a closer look at the variable.

The number of levels of continent in the first-hand data:

nlevels(gapminder$continent)
## [1] 5

And these levels are:

levels(gapminder$continent)
## [1] "Africa"   "Americas" "Asia"     "Europe"   "Oceania"

The number of rows of continent in the first-hand data:

nrow(gapminder)
## [1] 1704

At this point, we know for sure that the continent variable in the gapminder dataset is a factor. It contains 5 levels, namely Africa, Americas, Asia, Europe and Oceania, and 1704 rows in total. Then we can perform data manipulation by filtering the gapminder data to remove observations associated with the continent of Oceania and removing unused factor levels.

dropocn <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(continent != "Oceania")

DT::datatable(dropocn)
dropocn %>% 
  nrow()
## [1] 1680
dropocn$continent %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  nlevels()
## [1] 4
dropocn$continent %>% 
  droplevels() %>% 
  levels()
## [1] "Africa"   "Americas" "Asia"     "Europe"

After filtering and removing unused levels, the factor continent only contains 1680 rows in total and 4 levels(Africa, Americas, Asia and Europe). Oceania is now excluded from the dataset.

Reorder the levels of country or continent

Here, we need to change the order of the factor levels based on summary statistic of one quantitative variable. Take country as an example:

The statistic criteria I choose is minimun population over the years (1952 - 2007).

order <- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarize(minpop = min(pop))
DT::datatable(order)

Now it is still alphabetized in alphabetical order based on the first letter of the countrys name. This is how it looks like in a plot:

order %>% 
  ggplot(aes(minpop,country)) +
  geom_point()+
  scale_x_log10()+
  xlab("minimum population")+
  ylab("country")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Lets reorder it.

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(min_gdp = min(gdpPercap)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=min_gdp, y=country)) +
  geom_point() + 
  scale_x_log10()+
  labs(x="Minimum GDP per capita", y="Country", title = "Minimum GDP per capita by country over the years") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
